title: IoT Smart Drawer with Amazon Dash Replenishment Service

description.text:
https://youtu.be/NDodvE3VeLI

Whether you are working in an office or simply at home, the desk drawer is the go to place for small but important supplies. Its happened to all of us: You go to the drawer to get an item, whether that be a stamp, paperclip, or a piece of paper. You open the drawer only to find the item missing. Running to the store for such a small item is such a hassle, so you either get by with out it or waste precious time.

With the Smart Drawer, your essential office supplies are electronically monitored with the Particle Core, an IoT development board with WiFi. The board monitors your AA batteries with a break beam sensor, post it notes and paper clips with photoresistors, tape with a switch, stamps with a rotary encoder, and office paper with a load cell. When an item is running low, the Particle Core will make a request to the Amazon Cloud and automatically place an order for you, along with notifying you by email.

All of parts are 3D printed in ABS and welded together with acetone. For a full write up on this project check out my project page on Hackster: https://www.hackster.io/Mach_5/iot-smart-desk-drawer-with-amazon-drs-4bc528

title: Blinking Iris Goggles with Battery Holder

description.text:
In order to make some Blinking Iris Goggles with LED rings in the eyes, I'll need to supply it with power. Since there are already two strands of fishing line hanging from the goggles (to actuate the blinking), I decided to put a battery holder right on the goggles instead of having a wire going off into a pocket somewhere. I also wanted a way to detect actuation of the blink. I decided the best way to do this was have a small neodymium magnet glued to the rotating part of one of the eyes, and have it come near a reed switch which could be mounted to the battery box. I remixed the Right Eyeball file so it has a magnet holder that will accept a 5mm x 3mm magnet. The one in the video is a 4mm x 2mm.
I made the reed switch holder separately to aid with assembly and to add the ability to print it in a different color. It can be glued on the battery box. I do not have a way to mount a 5v regulator and a digispark, but for now, the battery box and switch holder will be enough to make a prototype.

title: Anet A6 (and A8) Mosfet Vertical Holder - Left Aligned

description.text:
After playing with another design I found Leo_N's excellent MOSFET holder (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2018906). The reason I like his design over others is that it allows for modular installation since it only uses 2 mainboard screws to attach to the printer. I bought 2 MOSFETs for my Anet A6 and thought I was going to mount both above the mainboard, but after seeing Leo_N's design I settled on installing the hotbed MOSFET below the mainboard using Leo_N's horizontal version and wanted to install the hot-end MOSFET above the board using Leo_N's vertical version. The issue I encountered was that the vertical version placed the MOSFET directly above the USB and microSD connectors so I flipped his small vertical version to put the MOSFET on the left when it is above the mainboard of the A6.

EDIT: I created a second version of this remix to move the MOSFET a bit higher because simply flipping the vertical holder from Leo_N puts the power terminals of the MOSFET too close to the microSD and USB connectors on the mainboard.

EDIT 2: Printed and installed It works very well. I hope you like the support and if you can improve on it please let me know.

It is fixed on a X axis with M3x10mm Hex screws + M3 T-Nuts.

My procedure for bed leveling:

  • fix the comparator on one side of the X axis (as on picture). Move Y axis until end, near the screw for bed. Move Z axis down with Repetier, until the comparator measure 1 mm exactly. Then move the Y axis to the next corner, then turn the bed screw until the comparator measure same 1mm. Move the comparator the other side of the X axis, and repeat the previous steps, keep Z at same height.

I got tired of my Fat Shark Lipo and wanted to do the 18650 battery mod, but I was not comfortable soldering directly onto the battery because i really didn't want to have a battery blow up in my face. Thus this was born. This case is designed to have battery contacts soldered on so no soldering iron ever touches the batteries. There is a channel down the center for the second cell balance wire to go in. After all wires are soldered and work you can then fill the cable tracks with hot glue to seal everything in. The nice part about this case is that if you have a separate 18650 battery charger, you only need one case and when the batteries die you can just swap them out. There are many ways to mount the lid, my way is to drill two small holes on opposite corners and the use heat set nuts on the bottom part then secure the lid with small bolts.

*If there is interest, I will design one that has room for a battery level indicator

Batteries: You need 2 18650 3.7 volt 3400mAh batteries

I received and assembled a FlashROM99 recently. It came as a bare board and I wanted a case to protect it.

Case is in two parts, the main case, and the cover
Before placing the board into the case make sure that the connector fits through the opening. Mine fit fine, but I would suggest check first incase you need to do any clean up. The rectangular area at the back of the case make removal of the cartridge easier.

The cover stays in place via a friction fit, so I found it easiest to insert the front corners first, then press the rest of the cover into place.

title: Maker Select Plus Z-Axis Level Feet

description.text:
I am totally new to 3D printing and was looking for a project that would give me experience and provide something useful. I appreciate the files provided by everyone on Thingiverse and other websites to help the rest of us to learn and contribute to others.

My project was based off a posting by Spool3d which was based off a project from Azziz and his original z brace design.

I used Azza's "Z braces for Wanhao Duplicator i3, Cocoon Create, Maker Select, and Malyan M150 i3 3D printers."
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:921948
Just print the top_right, top_left and 4 of the MK2 balls from Azza's braces.

I did a remix of Spool3D_canada,"z Brace for Wanhao Duplicator i3 PLUS".
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1653631

Print the 4 remixed files I have provided for the front left, front right, rear left and rear right.

I did purchase the following supplies from Home Depot:
Qty:1-5/16-18UNC X 36" threaded rod cut in half with hand saw
Qty 2: 5/16-18UNC Locknut, (goes to lower threaded rod in assembly)
Qty 4: 5/16-18UNC Hex Nut, (goes to Upper MK2 Balls, direction of ball important)
Qty 8: M3-0.5 X 12mm Socket Head Cap Screw (To replace upper brace screws)
Qty 4: M5-0 8 X12mm Socket Head Cap Screw (To replace front and rear face screws)
Qty 4: Threaded Furniture Glides (SKU 193 637) 1/4" thread with a press fit threaded plug
All items will be located in the fasteners/hardware section at the store

Be aware the unit could be considered heavy to some and an extra hand could be helpful. I inserted the rod and locknut into the lower supports first and slide the rod up towards the upper support, you must install the nut and ball (knurl down) and screw down about 2 inches prior to inserting the rod into the upper support. Next insert into the support and thread the nut and ball (knurl up) onto the top support. The length of rod and the angle can interfere with the machine support, you will need to thread nuts low enough for it to fit.

My leveling models have incorporated the threaded insert provided with the leveling feet, you will need to press fit them into the hole with a pliers or small vise.

title: Modified files for improved OpenRC Truggy printed parts performance
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
When I started printing the Open RC truggy, I found that it was EXTREMELY difficult to source parts in the UK. For example, the driveshafts from conrad are expensive, expensive to ship and usually out of stock. However, HSP 188015 driveshafts are massively cheap and are in abundance everywhere!

So, this is my OpenRC Truggy remix page where over the continuing build I shall upload all the files that I modify and my reasons for it to make the life easier of those wanting to have a go at printing this cool machine.

  1. 188015 axle shaft.
    Originally, this was designed for use with the conrad drive shafts which are expensive and difficult to source. I wanted to use the 188015 driveshafts which are the opposite. However, they are slightly too long for the original differential output shafts/axles.
    On top of this I found that my original redesign of the output shafts, whilst working, wasn't nearly strong enough. After several iterations of designs, I decided upon this final design making use of 4x 1mm dowel pins approx 10mm in length around the main screw. This adds a metal, positive drive to the shaft output. It's a little fiddly and I would recommend printing 100% infill and using a 1mm drill to clean holes and 2.5mm drill to clean centre hole to ease assembly. Also, pre-tap the centre hole with a screw to ease assembly.

You'll find that the holes in the outer axle shaft are slightly further apart than the sun gear, that's on purpose to ensure that the pins splay outwards when tightening as if they didn't they'll splay inwards and damage the screw.

  1. Rear C-Hub.
    I take issue where bearings are concerned. If you've got a 5mm shaft in a 5mm bearing, don't make the hole the shaft runs through 5mm also because the inner race of the bearing isn't 5mm, it's more like 7mm. That means when the bearing is pressed in, the inner race rubs up against the back edge of the hole it sits in causing the inner race to bind. With this mod, I've expanded the hole from 10.1mm to 10.2mm to ease fitment of bearings and reduce compression of the outer race (less binding/wear/longer life) AND made the internal hole 7mm so that the inner race runs clear and free and what a difference it made!

  2. Steering Pin.
    So trying to find the 5mm ball headed pins was also a pain in the rear, needlessly difficult and entirely uncommon. I've henceforth modified the steering pin cups to now accept the HSP 02038 ball head screws. It's a tight fit and to be fair, doesn't look very durable but I'll soon find out when I eventually get the car moving. This one is open to debate and if it's no good I'll increase the thickness around the open ends to strengthen it.

  3. Steering Block.
    Same reasoning as the rear C hub. Expanded the bearing holes for an easier bearing fitment and expanded the centre hole so that the bearing inner race isn't binding up on the hub.

  4. Steering part 1/2.
    Expanded the holes for an easier bearing fitment. Wasn't enough space to expand the centre hole to prevent the bearing inner race from binding on the part so instead I extruded a small shoulder, about 0.4mm, to raise the outer race away from the face of the hole, thereby moving the inner race away from the undersized hole and preventing any binding there

  5. Servo Holder
    I opted to use the MG996 servo as they're common as muck and just as cheap. However the servo holder was a little too small to hold it do I've modified the design to suit. Be sure to use the rubber grommets also

  6. Centre differential output shafts
    So after strengthening the front/rear diffs, it was then found that the centre diff was now susceptible to the same issue of snapping either the the input side square or output side joint. In response to this I applied the pin design to the shaft increasing the strength of the power train even more so.

title: Anet A8 Circular Extruder Fan - lowered (various lengths)

description.text:
Thanks Arjjck for the Hesine M-505 design!
I tried several circular extruder fans on my A8 but a lot seemed to be cooling the extruder itself and causing my temps to fluctuate so I decided to get the fan as low as I could to help minimize this. I attacked Arjjck's design with my limited knowledge of Meshmixer to extend the ring down and these are the results.
On my machine the 3mm (pictured) is very close to the bed/print and works well. The 4mm extension would probably scrape against my bed/print but maybe someone else can use it.
These fans will likely collide with any clips you may have around the edge of your heatbed so plan accordingly.

Ok, so I was watching this youtube video on how to make a turkey call from a prescription pill bottle....

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZRVkU7Yb7G4

Basically all you need is the body printed and a latex or nitrile glove. You cut a square out of the palm and a couple of rings out of one of the fingers then you stretch the square around the opening (leaving a little gap), then use the finger ring to hold it. The finger ring should fit nice into the groove designed into the body.

I designed these in TinkerCAD.

https://www.tinkercad.com/things/7J4GIFUciKj-turkey-call/editv2?sharecode=9axbyFXQGDZzUxkjy3O9a2cyMvY51FeNPttufhYLWBI=

And realized that I could design and print this fairly easily. All you will need is a latex glove to cut a piece out of and put over the top. I designed a cap to fit over the top, and a cap to fit over the bottom. I also put in an o-ring if you want to print that out of NinjaFlex or some other flexible material.

I haven't tested these yet, but I intend to print these on the shop's Zortrax fairly soon. So the fit of the caps may not be perfect. But I gave them the same tolerance that I do with everything. So they should work.

Update I tested the first design, and decided the call was a little too high in pitch. So I increased the diameter, and shortened the length, and ditched the top cap idea. So version 2 is printing now.

title: Cluster (the full sized) Stool
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
DOWNLOAD NOW ONLY AVAILABLE AT WWW.PONGOSTORE.COM

An elegant and minimalist stool that would not look out of place in the most modern of interior.
That's right this is a full sized stool for printing on your desktop 3D printer!

Simply choose your printing material, repeat the print 3 times, apply a generous coating of Pongo PLA Gel adhesive* to all joint faces. Other adhesives can of course be used if you know of a suitable one for the purpose, but we do not recommend sitting on this without it being properly glued together.
Once the adhesive is applied simply snap the parts together ensuring the top joints are sitting nice and flat. Place the assembly upside down on a flat surface (being sure to use a mat or newspaper) and simply leave overnight with some weight applied to the top, maybe a few thick books or 4 or 5 KG reels of Pongo filament ;)
Legs in unfinished oak or ash are available from G&S Specialist timber and for our stool we ordered lengths of 500mm. The diameter required is 35mm.
Please note that both your leg socket (created by your printer) and the timber leg diameter may vary slightly.
The design as created, is done so to create a tight fit of a 35mm leg, avoiding the need for screw fixings, but you may find that you need to sand or plane the end of the legs to get them to a snug fit. Alternatively you could wait until we upload the revised edition which will have a slightly larger socket size and some screw fixing holes. Other variations also to follow!

We will also be creating other stools for those of you with slightly narrower print beds. The current design requires a bed width (printable width) of 200mm but we are going to continue to develop and create a number of stools and many other products that will cater for those of you with printers that have a width of as low as 145mm. Please follow us on the social media channels for updates on other upcoming product launches.

*Please note that we do not recommend the use of the Pongo Activator that comes with the adhesive for this assembly, as such the adhesive may require a full 24 hours to achieve maximum strength.

Printing settings and tips:

  1. Use a raft for a consistent top finish and also to minimise the chance of the print pulling away from the bed.
  2. Supports are obviously needed due to the top overhang and for good measure we simply had supports all over. Keep the density to a minimum though.
  3. Fill density to not be less than 5% but we would recommend at least 10% to give a good amount of support between the leg and the top of the seat.
  4. For good measure we also used a glue stick on the print bed to increase adhesion as our first test print did peal away 3 hours in to the print, and with large prints you really don't want to take any chances. Seat belts and crash helmets required for this print if you want to leave it on autopilot overnight :)
  5. Layer height - We think this looks just fine at a resolution of 0.3.
  6. Not specifically related to this product print but a good tip non the less; If you do not yet have a pair then we would recommend you invest in a pair of cut resistant gloves (available from a number of vendors on Amazon) they really do help when you have those little slips cleaning off your stubborn support material.

Any other questions then please do message us here or on any of the social media sites.

Happy printing :)

Notes:

You can of course print this at higher resolution but it really does look just amazing at 0.3 so why wait any longer?
Supports are obviously a must due to the step in the top, but you could try bed only supports if you are brave. We have not yet tried this, but if you do decide to be brave and give it a go do let everyone know how this turns out as it could save everyone a half hour or so per print, and of course a few metres of filament :)

Assembly

The three printed parts will snap together quite easily and would make an excellent side table as such, but if you want to sit on this you then some extra strength is required.
For this we use our very own Pongo PLA Gel Adhesive available from the Pongo Store Apply liberally to one face of all joint surfaces.

Pongo - Design 4 Purpose

We wanted to create a stool that could be printed on a desktop printer but also one that did not rely on brackets or screw fixings etc that detract from the form and aesthetics. With its simple overlapping circular design the jointing detail and splayed legs of the Cluster stool actually creates its own natural strength that is actually improved when sat on. However as per the summary, we do recommend that the stool parts be glued together, as a twisting motion whilst sat on the seat could end in you sitting on the floor! :)
Once properly jointed the three components create a very robust stool top to which you can then add legs of your choosing. Please refer to the description for links to suppliers of suitable timber legs, and of course our very own Pongo PLA Gel Adhesive available from the Pongo Store

description.text:
So I was watching this youtube video about making a quail call out of a stick and a rubber band. Which I am doing, and will finish it eventually. Then I thought I would try a 3d printed one as well. So I designed it on TinkerCAD. I made two designs. One has guides to hold the two halves together straight. The first one does not. (UPDATE the one with the guides I've ditched for now.) Whichever one you choose you will have to print two of them and put them together. I also designed in a ring for an o-ring to hold them together straight. Just in case you are so inclined as to hunt down an o-ring the appropriate size. I also included the oring if you want to 3d print one out of flexible material.

UPDATE I temporarily removed one of the designs (the one with the guides on it. Until I can get the first one tested and perfected. I actually don't think it's necessary so I'm ditching that one for now. My first design was a bit too big, so I made it smaller, and I also made the blow hole smaller, it was too big too.

I've perfected the design, I think for now anyway. It sounds pretty spot on, but I haven't had the chance to take it into the bush yet. In the picture I show that I've used o-rings to fasten one side and a rubber band to fasten the other. This is to just to show that you can do either and they work equally well. I also use a strip of "Theraband Gold" for the reed. That's because I have some on hand for my sling shots and I can cut them to any width and length. It works pretty well, but you should be able to use rubber bands just as well, a nice thick one methinks.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aooYTCv078k

You'll need to watch the video to see how and what to make a reed out of.

3d Printed Hat Block This project is a reproduction of an original 1940's hat block scanned and edited for optimal printing.
This particular file has high infil and is very sturdy. However the infil can be reduced while maintaining the integrity of the block.
The product is extremely sturdy and can be used with both straw and felt blocking techniques. However, when blocking with felt please keep in mind the tendency of plastic to melt and avoid hitting the uncovered block directly with steam or touching it directly with hot tools. Steaming the hat while on the block seems to be alright. In addition, the block itself is not pinnable however, if attached to a wooden base (instructions given) it functions perfectly.

description.text:
I recently bought Bomberman Live for my Xbox One and the memories came flooding back. I wanted a model to print but I could only find one tiny one so I made my own.

UPDATE 5/15/17: I've finally printed this! I printed it at 75% scale (see bottle for scale). All printed in Gizmodorks PLA, 0.2mm layers and 25% infill. I changed the bomb, body and head to each be two pieces which makes them easier to print. I just used hot glue to stick the parts together.

I also made a flame that I'm going ot light with an LED with a flickering effect. I'll put a 500mAh LiPo and an Adafruit Trinket inside the bomb. I made a hollow version of the bomb fuse to facilitate running wires to the LED. I'm going to either paint the fuse with tan paint or reprint it with a sample of ColorFabb Woodfill I have coming.

I printed the head in white then used Testors gloss cream enamel model paint for the face, gloss black for the eyes and gloss yellow for the belt buckle. I also added the eyebrows and tacked them above the eyes with hot glue.

For the belt I printed the top half of the body starting with black PLA then switched to red after the belt layer to avoid needing to paint the belt afterwards.

I HAVE NOT PRINTED THIS YET so I have no ideas for print settings or anything yet. Hopefully in the coming weeks I can get it printed and assembled. I'm sure some parts will require support The legs, arms and antenna support can probably be printed with 0% infill so you have just a hollow shell and won't need to use a lot of filament.

Each piece is separate so you can print in the color of your choice. The head and helmet are one piece so you can paint the face. The body and belt are also one piece so they will require painting as well.

I've uploaded the STL's as well as the Inventor files. I've also uploaded both the one-piece and two-piece versions of the head, bomb and body.

title: Clear top Robo R1 & R1+ partial enclosure

description.text:
I replaced my old enclosure design with this one that is easier to make.
This one requires only printing 4 side pieces and seam re-enforcements along with magnetic mounts. outer side braces are optional.
You can now use any thickness clear acrylic sheet or plexi glass. But I recommend 2mm thickness or close to it that you can get at Lowe's Home Improvement.
Magnets are round 12mmX6mm you can purchase on Amazon or E-bay

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

medium

Infill:

15%

Notes:

Use PLA or any other filament that does not warp easily.

Parts to purchase and cut and assembly

Purchase 16 12X6 mm round rare earth Magnets, from Ebay or Amazon.
Purchase two 24"X18" sheets of clear acrylic in your desired thickness.(one sheet per enclosure)
Purchase a clear wall corner protector available at Lowes for $2.97 for a 48" long piece
Size to cut acrlyc:
Front 10 15/16" X 9 3/16"
Top. 10 13/16" X 6 9/16"
You will need two of each of these for the printer
Assemble 2 sets of sides using the corresponding side re-enforcements using your preferred gluing method.
First install the top clear acrylic sheet to both sides and let the glue cure.
Glue the magnets into the magnet holders and let cure. you should have a total of 8 magnet holders.
Glue the magnet Holders to the sides on the enclosure one near the top and one on the sloped part of the sides that will sit against the printer. see pictures if you have questions on location.
Hold the enclosure up to the printer and place a magnet inside the printer in each of the four locations that are on the enclosure. the magnets hould now hold the enclosure in place. One at a time remove each magnet and put glue on the side that goes against the inside of the printer then replace it where it was removed. Do this for each magnet.
after the glue cures remove the enclosure and glue the front acrylic piece to the enclosure and let cure.
Cut the clear corner protector to a length of 10" and use it to connect the top and front together.
If desired add the outer side braces.
This completes the assembly.

Designed this for my 35 gallon reef tank in conjunction with a powerhead to help when I move things arounds and stir up the bed. This way I can turn off my main filter (eheim pro3) and let this filter pull the suspended material out of the water column. I use a 375 gph powerhead on the bottom mounted upside down to pull water through the filter back into tank. You'll have to drill your own hole to suit your specific brand of powerhead. I use 6 layers of fine filter floss to for filtering with no carbon. If your power head has an air adapter use it as the bubbles produced are very fine and you can mount it at such a height it removes protein from the water as well as surface skims. Saltwater fish aren't crazy about the bubbles so I do not use it for extended periods of time. I design did to be pretty thick for durability. Good luck and I'm open to suggestions for improvement.
